    "created_at": "2018-07-28T02:49:36Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-07-28T02:49:36Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "(This is the only test currently failing for me when I run pytest on pandas off the binary Linux wheel on Python 2.7. It's clearly a benign failure, but as the only one failing, it seems reasonable to fix.)\r\n\r\nAt a glance, looks like test_info_repr assumes that the default value for the max_columns config option is 20, but this is only true if you're not running in a terminal ([see here](https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/blob/c9e8f59668b63738cccb913f837c529887097da1/pandas/core/config_init.py#L318)). I suspect this wasn't noticed because other people may be running their tests from outside a terminal? Anyway, the issue was introduced by c9e8f59668b63738cccb913f837c529887097da1. The most reasonable solution seems to be to wrap the `assert has_horizontally_truncated_repr(df)` in an `option_context` setting `display.max_columns` to `max_cols`."
